target_title: Resolves https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gimp/-/issues/12368

note.body:
@ok  Hello, sorry about the confusion on IRC earlier today. Anyhow, GEGL 0.4.52 is releasing soon and this problem  (as of 1.5 months ago) is completely solved by replacing  gegl:layer with gegl:load.                  

Remember the entirety of the problem explained in three parts.

1. gegl:layer's image upload was causing gegl:crop to crash if it had an aux.  Issue here, https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gimp/-/issues/12368

2. gegl:crop without an aux doesn't work on layer groups

3. gegl:innerglow without a crop causes glitch artifacts (issue GEGL #392

The reason I was pushing stupid updates was because I was confused on what to do with gegl:layer crashing GIMP but after replacing gegl:layer with gegl:load all problems are solved and this is the final update to GEGL Styles unless it gets new features in the future. When you get the time please review, thanks.

GeglAbyssPolicy not properly introspected/able

note.body:
I realize it's even less a problem than expected because for the issue of operation-visible only enum types, I in fact special cases all `GeglParamEnum` arguments to be set as string.

This is for instance how we'd set a "gegl:edge" on a drawable in script-fu:

```scm
(gimp-drawable-merge-new-filter active-layer "gegl:edge" 0 LAYER-MODE-REPLACE opacity "amount" 2.0 "border-behavior" "none" "algorithm" "sobel")
```

So I don't even need access to `GEGL-ABYSS-NONE` (or other enum values) in fact, at least not for this new procedure usage. Maybe for something else though, and technically it would still be nice if that were introspected into Script-fu. But well… for the time being, it's even less a priority and good for backlog enhancement for maybe a future major version…

Different cpus give different hash results when building gegl

note.body:
There is two different goals at odds with each other, performance and the desire for bit-exact outputs for regression discovery. On x86-64 GEGL is built  for three different microarchitectures, some instructions/compiler options might even be increasing precision, like fused multiply add. Most of the hashes used as references matched on my previous laptop, I am now on arm64 and lots of hashes are wrong.

The previous regression testing in GEGL which still has remnants and also breaks on arm64 vs x86_64 used images and differences with a little bit of slack, checking in PNG reference images bloats the git repo, and is thus best avoided.

gegel 0.4.50 build failure due to undefined reference to `babl_space_is_rgb'

note.body:
We've been artificially keeping the required babl version low due to newer babls depending on fresher meson versions than available in old distros we've wanted to keep working with gimp-2.10. GIMP-3 depends on babl-0.1.110 so a build of GIMP would fail later even if GEGL accepts it, in practice one should always build the latest release or even git master of babl/GEGL when building GIMP.

I think there is value in keeping gimp-2.10 working a little longer, at least until gimp 3 actually is the new stable.

note.body:
This seems to be neither needed nor working (at least I got an error): 
```
terminate called after throwing an instance of 'std::length_error'
  what():  basic_string::append
sh: line 1: 57795 Abort trap              /opt/local/bin/ninja -j6 -v
```
AFAIU, `-xobjective-c` is passed only as a C flag, we do not need anything special in ldflags, just drop offending `-ObjC`.

Perhaps, gcc and clang need distinct cased, so nothing is accidentally broken. Let clangs use their `-ObjC`, and gcc can use `-xobjective-c`.

target_title: gegl 0.4.50 fails to build on macOS with GCC

note.body:
@lukaso Thank you, I will try. I am not sure this gonna work as a linker flag; I did not need any with gcc, only C flag. But we need to check if it is breaking or not.

UPD. I have replied in the PR now. AFAICT, `-xobjective-c` should be used as a C flag, and `-ObjC` obviously removed from either when building with gcc (even though upstream adds its support in gcc15, no point requiring it). I think it should be easier to merge and safer to maintain if gcc and clang are separate cases there, rather than having one-size-fits-all, which can be easily broken again on subsequent update, since no one tests gcc on macOS.

target_title: gegl, operations: add infrastructure to query older versions of an operation.

note.body: For info, I'll get back to this after RC1, or maybe even after 3.0 release. In any case, GIMP is now storing the version of GEGL ops in XCF files and will just discard op versions it cannot process. This is the important part because it creates future-proof XCF files which GIMP/GEGL will be able to read once we add the "older version running" infra set. So it's not a release blocker.
